          <th>Use Case</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;wbr&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Optional &mdash; only if needed</td>
          <td>URLs, long words, CJK mixed text</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;br&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Forced &mdash; always breaks</td>
          <td>Addresses, poetry, structured text</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="wbr vs br">{{ wbrVsBrCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS Alternatives</h2>
    <p>Consider CSS solutions when <code>&lt;wbr&gt;</code> would be tedious to insert manually:</p>
    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>CSS Property</th><th>Effect</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>overflow-wrap: break-word</code></td>
          <td>Break long words at any point to prevent overflow</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>word-break: break-all</code></td>
          <td>Break between any two characters (aggressive, used by VB for CJK)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>hyphens: auto</code></td>
          <td>Insert hyphens at syllable boundaries (used by VB's <code>p.justify</code>)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Use <code>&lt;wbr&gt;</code> when you need precise control over <em>where</em> breaks can occur.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS Reference</h2>
    <code-block language="css" label="wbr CSS">{{ wbrCssCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>VB explicitly sets <code>display: inline</code> to ensure consistent behavior. The element is a void element (no closing tag) and inserts no visible content.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><code>&lt;wbr&gt;</code> has no effect on screen readers &mdash; it is purely visual</li>
      <li>The break is invisible; it only affects where line wrapping can occur</li>
      <li>Text content remains intact and continuous for assistive technologies</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

